lver-spangled jacket. She persevered: “Well?” “And your hairdo is most becoming.” “Oh, what does it matter,” she wailed, “what on earth does anything matter!” “I must be on my way,” he whispered with a smile and got up. “Kiss me,” she said, and was like a limp, shivering ragdoll in his arms for a moment.

He walked to the gate. At the turn of the path he glanced back and saw in the distance her white figure with the listless grace of ineffable grief bending over the garde